            "description": "Write a Python function called `has_duplicates` that takes a list as input and returns True if the list contains any duplicate elements, and False otherwise.\nExamples:\n  has_duplicates([1, 2, 3, 2]) → True\n  has_duplicates([1, 2, 3]) → False\n  has_duplicates(['a', 'b', 'a']) → True",
            "initialCode": "def has_duplicates(lst):\n    pass\n\ndef has_duplicates():\n    pass\n\ndef has_duplicates():\n    pass\n\ndef has_duplicates(elements):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef has_duplicates(lst):\n    unique = set()  # Set to track elements we've seen\n    common = []\n    for word in lst:\n        if word in unique:\n            common.append(word)  # Add to common list (optional)\n            return True  # Found duplicate, return True immediately\n        else:\n            unique.add(word)  # Add to set of seen elements\n    return False  # No duplicates found, return False\nlst = ['it', 'was', 'itt']\nprint(has_duplicates(lst))  # Output: False\ndef has_duplicates():\n    user = input('type list: ').split()\n    unique = set()\n    for word in user:\n        if word in unique:\n            print('True')\n            return True\n        unique.add(word)\n    print('False')    \n    return False\nhas_duplicates()\ndef has_duplicates():\n    user = input('type list: ').split()\n    unique = set()\n    for word in user:\n        if word in unique:\n            return True\n        unique.add(word)\n    return False \nprint(has_duplicates())\ndef has_duplicates(elements):\n    duplicate = set()\n    for element in elements:\n        if element in duplicate:\n            return True\n        duplicate.add(element)\n    return False\nlist_with_duplicates = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 2]\nlist_without_duplicates = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nprint('Does the list have duplicates?', has_duplicates(list_with_duplicates))\n\n# Alternative solution using len() comparison\ndef has_duplicates(lst):\n    return len(lst) != len(set(lst))\nprint(has_duplicates([1, 2, 3, 2]))  # Output: True\nprint(has_duplicates([1, 2, 3]))     # Output: False\n\n# Alternative solution using list comprehension\ndef has_duplicates(lst):\n    return any(lst.count(x) > 1 for x in lst)\nprint(has_duplicates(['a', 'b', 'a']))  # Output: True\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef has_duplicates(lst):\n    return [word for word in lst]\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef has_duplicates(lst):\n    return list(map(lambda word: word, lst))\n\n# Script approach\nlst = [2, 4, 6, 8]\nresult = has_duplicates(lst)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(has_duplicates([1, 3, 5, 7]))",

