            "description": "Write a Python function called `reverse_number` that takes an integer as input and returns the reverse of that number. For example, if the input is 123, the function should return 321.\n  reverse_number(123) → 321\n  reverse_number(900) → 9\n  reverse_number(5) → 5",
            "initialCode": "def reverse_number(number):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef reverse_number(number):\n    return int(str(number)[::-1])  # Returns reversed number\nnumber = 123\nprint(reverse_number(number))  # Output: 321\n\n# Alternative solution using math operations\ndef reverse_number(number):\n    reversed_num = 0\n    num = abs(number)\n    while num > 0:\n        digit = num % 10\n        reversed_num = reversed_num * 10 + digit\n        num //= 10\n    return reversed_num if number >= 0 else -reversed_num\nprint(reverse_number(-456))  # Output: -654\nprint(reverse_number(1000))  # Output: 1\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef reverse_number(number):\n    result = int(str(number)[::-1])\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef reverse_number(number):\n    return int(str(number)[::-1])\n\n# Script approach\nnumber = 15\nresult = reverse_number(number)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(reverse_number(25))",

