            "initialCode": "def find_index(numbers, target):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef find_index(numbers, target):\n    for index, num in enumerate(numbers):\n        if num == target:\n            return index  # Return index immediately when found\n    return -1  # Target not found\nnumbers = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9]\ntarget = 5\nprint('Index of', target, 'in nums:', find_index(numbers, target))  # Output: Index of 5 in nums: 2\ntarget = 6\nprint('Index of', target, 'in nums:', find_index(numbers, target))  # Output: Index of 6 in nums: -1\n\n# Alternative solution using index() method with try-except\ndef find_index(numbers, target):\n    try:\n        return numbers.index(target)\n    except ValueError:\n        return -1\nprint(find_index([10, 20, 30, 40], 30))  # Output: 2\nprint(find_index([10, 20, 30, 40], 50))  # Output: -1\n\n# Alternative solution using list comprehension\ndef find_index(numbers, target):\n    indices = [i for i, num in enumerate(numbers) if num == target]\n    return indices[0] if indices else -1\nprint(find_index([5, 10, 15, 20], 15))  # Output: 2\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef find_index(numbers, target):\n    result = index\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef find_index(numbers, target):\n    return index\n\n# Script approach\nnumbers = [3, 7, 2, 9, 1]\ntarget = 'target'\nresult = find_index(numbers, target)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(find_index([4, 1, 8, 6, 3], 'goal'))",

