            "initialCode": "def count_words(s):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef count_words(s):\n    s = s.lower()\n    words = s.split()  # ['this', 'is', 'a', 'test', 'this', 'test', ...]\n    word_count = {}  # Dictionary to store word frequencies\n    for word in words:\n        if word in word_count:\n            word_count[word] += 1  # Increment count if word exists\n        else:\n            word_count[word] = 1\n    return word_count  # Return dictionary with word counts\ninput_string = 'This is a test. This test is only a test.'\nprint(count_words(input_string))  # Output: {'this': 2, 'is': 2, 'a': 2, 'test.': 2, 'only': 1}\n\n# Alternative solution using Counter\ndef count_words(s):\n    from collections import Counter\n    return dict(Counter(s.lower().split()))\nprint(count_words('hello world hello'))  # Output: {'hello': 2, 'world': 1}\n\n# Alternative solution using dict.get\ndef count_words(s):\n    word_count = {}\n    for word in s.lower().split():\n        word_count[word] = word_count.get(word, 0) + 1\n    return word_count\nprint(count_words('one two one'))  # Output: {'one': 2, 'two': 1}\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef count_words(s):\n    result = word_count\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef count_words(s):\n    return word_count\n\n# Script approach\ns = 'hello'\nresult = count_words(s)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(count_words('world'))",

