            "description": "Write a Python program to sort a list of numbers in ascending order. Prompt the user to enter a list of numbers.\nExamples:\n  ascending_order_numbers([5, 2, 8, 1, 9]) → [1, 2, 5, 8, 9]\n  ascending_order_numbers([64, 34, 25, 12, 22]) → [12, 22, 25, 34, 64]",
            "initialCode": "def main():\n    pass\n\ndef ascending_order_numbers(numbers):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef main():\n    result = []  # List to store converted integers\n    user = input('enter list of numbers: ')  # e.g., '56 23 677 6 1'\n    user = user.split()  # Split into list: ['56', '23', '677', '6', '1']\n    for num in user:\n        result.append(int(num))  # [56, 23, 677, 6, 1]\n    return sorted(result)  # Return sorted list: [1, 6, 23, 56, 677]\nmain()  # Call function (return value not printed)\ndef ascending_order_numbers(numbers):\n    sort_numbers = sorted(numbers)  # [56, 23, 677, 6, 1] \\u2192 [1, 6, 23, 56, 677]\n    return sort_numbers  # Return sorted list\nnumbers = [56, 23, 677, 6, 1]\nprint(ascending_order_numbers(numbers))  # Output: [1, 6, 23, 56, 677]\n\n# Alternative solution using list.sort()\ndef ascending_order_numbers(numbers):\n    result = numbers.copy()\n    result.sort()\n    return result\nprint(ascending_order_numbers([5, 2, 8, 1, 9]))  # Output: [1, 2, 5, 8, 9]\n\n# Alternative solution using bubble sort\ndef ascending_order_numbers(numbers):\n    arr = numbers.copy()\n    n = len(arr)\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(0, n-i-1):\n            if arr[j] > arr[j+1]:\n                arr[j], arr[j+1] = arr[j+1], arr[j]\n    return arr\nprint(ascending_order_numbers([64, 34, 25, 12, 22]))  # Output: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64]\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef main():\n    copy = result.copy()\n    copy.sort()\n    return copy\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef main():\n    return sorted(result, reverse=False)\n\n# Script approach\nnumbers = [3, 7, 2, 9, 1]\nresult = ascending_order_numbers(numbers)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(ascending_order_numbers([4, 1, 8, 6, 3]))",

