            "id": 83,
            "title": "Problem 83",
            "description": "Write a Python program to check if a given string is a palindrome using a recursive function. Prompt the user to enter a string.\nExamples:\n  is_palindrome('A man a plan a canal Panama') → True\n  is_palindrome('racecar') → True",
            "initialCode": "def is_palindrome(s):\n    pass\n\ndef main():\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef is_palindrome(s):\n    s = s.replace(' ', '').lower()  # 'Race Car' \\u2192 'racecar'\n    return s == s[::-1]  # 'racecar' == 'racecar' \\u2192 True\ndef main():\n    user_input = input('Enter a string: ')  # e.g., 'racecar'\n    if is_palindrome(user_input):\n        print(f'{user_input} is a palindrome.')  # Display success message\n    else:\n        print(f'{user_input} is not a palindrome.')  # Display failure message\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()  # Call main function\n\n# Alternative solution using two pointers\ndef is_palindrome(s):\n    s = s.replace(' ', '').lower()\n    left, right = 0, len(s) - 1\n    while left < right:\n        if s[left] != s[right]:\n            return False\n        left += 1\n        right -= 1\n    return True\nprint(is_palindrome('A man a plan a canal Panama'))  # Output: True\n\n# Alternative solution using recursion\ndef is_palindrome(s):\n    s = s.replace(' ', '').lower()\n    if len(s) <= 1:\n        return True\n    if s[0] != s[-1]:\n        return False\n    return is_palindrome(s[1:-1])\nprint(is_palindrome('racecar'))  # Output: True\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef is_palindrome(s):\n    result = s == s[::-1]\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef is_palindrome(s):\n    return s == s[::-1]\n\n# Script approach\ns = 'hello'\nresult = is_palindrome(s)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(is_palindrome('world'))",

            "hint": "`text == text[::-1]` is the simplest palindrome check.",
            "breakdown": "1. Prompt the user to enter a string.\n2. Define the `is_palindrome` function with a parameter `s` for the input string.\n3. Inside `is_palindrome`, check if the length of the string is less than or equal to 1. If so, return `True` because a single character or an empty string is always a palindrome.\n4. If the length of the string is greater than 1, recursively call `is_palindrome` on the substring from the second character to the end (`s[1:]`). This step checks if the first and last characters are the same.\n5. If the recursive call returns `True`, it means the rest of the string is a palindrome, so return `True`.\n6. If the recursive call returns `False`, it means the first and last characters are not the same, so return `False`.\n7. Define the `main` function to handle user input.\n8. Inside `main`, prompt the user to enter a string using `input()`.\n9. Call `is_palindrome` with the user's input as an argument.\n10. Print the result of `is_palindrome`.",

