            "description": "Write a Python program to find the LCM (Least Common Multiple) of two numbers. Prompt the user to enter two numbers.\nExamples:\n  lcm(12, 18) → 36\n  lcm(5, 7) → 35\n  lcm(4, 6) → 12",
            "initialCode": "def gcd(a, b):\n    pass\n\ndef lcm(a, b):\n    pass\n\ndef main():\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef gcd(a, b):\n    while b != 0:\n        a, b = b, a % b\n    return a\ndef lcm(a, b):\n    return abs(a * b) // gcd(a, b)  # abs() handles negative numbers, // is integer division\ndef main():\n    num1 = int(input('Enter the first number: '))\n    num2 = int(input('Enter the second number: '))\n    result_lcm = lcm(num1, num2)\n    print(f'The LCM of {num1} and {num2} is: {result_lcm}')\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n\n# Alternative solution using math.lcm (Python 3.9+)\ndef lcm(a, b):\n    import math\n    return math.lcm(a, b)\nprint(lcm(12, 18))  # Output: 36\nprint(lcm(5, 7))    # Output: 35\n\n# Alternative solution using list comprehension\ndef lcm(a, b):\n    for i in range(max(a, b), a * b + 1, max(a, b)):\n        if i % b == 0:\n            return i\nprint(lcm(4, 6))  # Output: 12\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef gcd(a, b):\n    result = a\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef gcd(a, b):\n    return a\n\n# Script approach\na = 10\nb = 20\nresult = gcd(a, b)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(gcd(20, 30))",

