            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef largest_smallest(elements):\n    smallest = elements[0]  # Start with first element as minimum\n    largest = elements[0]   # Start with first element as maximum\n    for element in elements:\n        if element < smallest:\n            smallest = element  # Found a new minimum\n        if element > largest:\n            largest = element  # Found a new maximum\n    return smallest, largest  # Returns tuple (smallest, largest)\n# Smallest: 1, Largest: 100\nlst = [4, 5, 100, 6, 1, 10]\nprint(largest_smallest(lst))  # Output: (1, 100)\n\n# Alternative solution using min() and max()\ndef largest_smallest(elements):\n    return min(elements), max(elements)\nprint(largest_smallest([10, 3, 7, 1, 9]))  # Output: (1, 10)\n\n# Alternative solution using reduce\ndef largest_smallest(elements):\n    from functools import reduce\n    smallest = reduce(lambda a, b: a if a < b else b, elements)\n    largest = reduce(lambda a, b: a if a > b else b, elements)\n    return smallest, largest\nprint(largest_smallest([4, 5, 100, 6, 1, 10]))  # Output: (1, 100)\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef largest_smallest(elements):\n    result = smallest, largest\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef largest_smallest(elements):\n    return smallest, largest\n\n# Script approach\nelements = [2, 7, 1, 9]\nresult = largest_smallest(elements)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(largest_smallest([5, 3, 8, 4]))",

