            "description": "Write a Python program to check if a number is an Armstrong number. An Armstrong number is a number that is equal to the sum of its own digits, each raised to the power of the number of digits. Prompt the user to enter a number.\nExamples:\n  is_armstrong(153) → True\n  is_armstrong(9474) → True\n  is_armstrong(123) → False",
            "initialCode": "def is_armstrong(number):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef is_armstrong(number):\n    digits = []\n    for digit in str(number):  # Convert to string to iterate over digits\n        digits.append(int(digit))  # Convert each digit back to int\n    power = len(digits)  # Power is number of digits\n    total = 0\n    for digit in digits:\n        total += digit ** power  # Add digit raised to power\n    return total == number  # Check if sum equals original number\nnumber = int(input('Enter a number: '))\nif is_armstrong(number):\n    print(f'{number} is an Armstrong number.')\nelse:\n    print(f'{number} is not an Armstrong number.')\nprint(number)\n\n# Alternative solution using list comprehension\ndef is_armstrong(number):\n    digits = [int(d) for d in str(number)]\n    power = len(digits)\n    return sum(d ** power for d in digits) == number\nprint(is_armstrong(153))   # Output: True (1^3 + 5^3 + 3^3 = 153)\nprint(is_armstrong(9474))  # Output: True\nprint(is_armstrong(123))   # Output: False\n\n# Alternative solution using while loop\ndef is_armstrong(number):\n    num = number\n    power = len(str(number))\n    total = 0\n    while num > 0:\n        digit = num % 10\n        total += digit ** power\n        num //= 10\n    return total == number\nprint(is_armstrong(370))  # Output: True\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef is_armstrong(number):\n    if total == number:\n        return True\n    return False\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef is_armstrong(number):\n    return (total == number)\n\n# Script approach\nnumber = 15\nresult = is_armstrong(number)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(is_armstrong(25))",

