            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef second_smallest_element():\n    user_input = input('Enter numbers separated by spaces: ')\n    int_numbers = []\n    for num_str in user_input.split():\n        int_numbers.append(int(num_str))\n    sorted_numbers = sorted(int_numbers)  # Sort ascending\n    if len(sorted_numbers) >= 2:\n        return sorted_numbers[1]  # Second element (index 1)\n    else:\n        return 'List should contain at least two numbers.'\nprint(second_smallest_element())\ndef second_smallest_element(elements):\n    if len(elements) < 2:\n        return None\n    sorted_elements = sorted(elements, key=len)  # key=len sorts by length, not value\n    return sorted_elements[1]  # Returns second shortest, not second smallest\narg = ['Jonathan', 'hot', 'sand']\nprint(second_smallest_element(arg))\n\n# Alternative solution using set and sorted\ndef second_smallest_element(elements):\n    unique = sorted(set(elements))\n    return unique[1] if len(unique) >= 2 else None\nprint(second_smallest_element([5, 3, 1, 4, 2]))  # Output: 2\n\n# Alternative solution using heapq\ndef second_smallest_element(elements):\n    import heapq\n    return heapq.nsmallest(2, set(elements))[1]\nprint(second_smallest_element([10, 5, 3, 8]))  # Output: 5\n\n# Alternative solution manual two-pass\ndef second_smallest_element(elements):\n    smallest = min(elements)\n    second = max(elements)\n    for x in elements:\n        if smallest < x < second:\n            second = x\n    return second\nprint(second_smallest_element([7, 2, 9, 1, 5]))  # Output: 2\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef second_smallest_element():\n    result = sorted_numbers[1]\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef second_smallest_element():\n    return sorted_numbers[1]\n\n# Script approach\nelements = [2, 7, 1, 9]\nresult = second_smallest_element(elements)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(second_smallest_element([5, 3, 8, 4]))",

