            "description": "Write a Python program to generate all possible permutations of a given string.\nExamples:\n  generate_permutations(\"AB\") → [\"AB\", \"BA\"]\n  generate_permutations(\"ABC\") → [\"ABC\", \"ACB\", \"BAC\", \"BCA\", \"CAB\", \"CBA\"]",
            "initialCode": "from itertools import permutations  # itertools.permutations generates all arrangements\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    pass\n\nimport itertools",
            "solution": "from itertools import permutations  # itertools.permutations generates all arrangements\n\n# Using function approach\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    result = []\n    for p in permutations(string):  # permutations() returns tuples of characters\n        result.append(''.join(p))  # join() converts tuple to string\n    return result\nstring = input('Enter a string: ')\nresult = generate_permutations(string)\nprint('Permutations:', result)\nimport itertools\nstring = 'abcd'\nresult = itertools.permutations(string)  # Returns iterator\nprint(list(result))  # Convert iterator to list\n\n# Alternative solution using list comprehension with permutations\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    from itertools import permutations\n    return [''.join(p) for p in permutations(string)]\nprint(generate_permutations('abc'))  # Output: ['abc', 'acb', 'bac', 'bca', 'cab', 'cba']\n\n# Alternative solution using recursive backtracking\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    result = []\n    def backtrack(path, remaining):\n        if not remaining:\n            result.append(path)\n        for i in range(len(remaining)):\n            backtrack(path + remaining[i], remaining[:i] + remaining[i+1:])\n    backtrack('', string)\n    return result\nprint(generate_permutations('ab'))  # Output: ['ab', 'ba']\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    result = result\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef generate_permutations(string):\n    return result\n\n# Script approach\nstring = 'hello'\nresult = generate_permutations(string)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(generate_permutations('world'))",

