            "initialCode": "def max_of_three(lst):\n    pass\n\ndef main(a, b, c):\n    pass\n\ndef max_of_three(a, b, c):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef max_of_three(lst):\n    largest = 0\n    for num in lst:\n        if num > largest:\n            largest = num\n    return largest\nlst = [466,45677,3]\nmax_of_three(lst)\ndef main(a, b, c):\n    return max(a,b,c)  # Built-in max() can take multiple arguments\nmain(56,8,445)\ndef max_of_three(a, b, c):\n    if a >= b and a >= c:  # Check if a is largest\n        return a\n    elif b >= a and b >= c:  # Check if b is largest\n        return b\n    else:  # Otherwise c is largest\n        return c\nmax_of_three()\n\n# Alternative solution using sorted\ndef max_of_three(a, b, c):\n    return sorted([a, b, c])[-1]\nprint(max_of_three(10, 25, 15))  # Output: 25\n\n# Alternative solution using ternary\ndef max_of_three(a, b, c):\n    return a if a >= b and a >= c else (b if b >= c else c)\nprint(max_of_three(100, 50, 75))  # Output: 100\n\n# Alternative solution using reduce\ndef max_of_three(a, b, c):\n    from functools import reduce\n    return reduce(lambda x, y: x if x > y else y, [a, b, c])\nprint(max_of_three(7, 3, 11))  # Output: 11\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef max_of_three(lst):\n    result = largest\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef max_of_three(lst):\n    return largest\n\n# Script approach\nlst = [2, 4, 6, 8]\nresult = max_of_three(lst)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(max_of_three([1, 3, 5, 7]))",

