            "description": "Write a Python function called count_words that takes a string as input and returns a dictionary where the keys are the words in the string and the values are the counts of each word. Words are separated by spaces, and the function should be case-insensitive, make the keys alphabetical.\nExamples:\n  count_words('one two one two three') → {'one': 2, 'three': 1, 'two': 2}\n  count_words('hello hello world') → {'hello': 2, 'world': 1}",
            "initialCode": "def count_words():\n    pass\n\ndef count_words(string):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef count_words():\n    user = input('type words: ').split()\n    sort = sorted(user)  # Sort words alphabetically\n    result = {}  # Dictionary to store word counts\n    for word in sort:\n        word = word.lower()  # Convert to lowercase for case-insensitive counting\n        if word in result:  # Dictionary membership check\n            result[word] += 1  # Increment count if word exists\n        else:\n            result[word] = 1\n    print(result)\ncount_words()\ndef count_words(string):\n    string = string.lower()  # Case-insensitive: convert entire string to lowercase\n    words = string.split()  # Split into words\n    word_count = {}  # Dictionary for word frequencies\n    for word in words:\n        if word in word_count:\n            word_count[word] += 1  # Increment existing count\n        else:\n            word_count[word] = 1\n    sorted_word_count = dict(sorted(word_count.items()))  # Sort dictionary by keys\n    return sorted_word_count\ninput_string = 'This is a test. This test is only a test.'\nprint(count_words(input_string))\n\n# Alternative solution using collections.Counter\ndef count_words(string):\n    from collections import Counter\n    return dict(sorted(Counter(string.lower().split()).items()))\nprint(count_words('This is a test. This test is only a test.'))\n\n# Alternative solution using dict.get()\ndef count_words(string):\n    words = string.lower().split()\n    count = {}\n    for word in words:\n        count[word] = count.get(word, 0) + 1\n    return dict(sorted(count.items()))\nprint(count_words('one two one two three'))  # Output: {'one': 2, 'three': 1, 'two': 2}\n\n# Alternative solution using setdefault\ndef count_words(string):\n    words = string.lower().split()\n    count = {}\n    for word in words:\n        count.setdefault(word, 0)\n        count[word] += 1\n    return dict(sorted(count.items()))\nprint(count_words('hello hello world'))  # Output: {'hello': 2, 'world': 1}\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef count_words():\n    user = input('type words: ').split()\n    sort = sorted(user)  # Sort words alphabetically\n    result = {}  # Dictionary to store word counts\n    for word in sort:\n        word = word.lower()  # Convert to lowercase for case-insensitive counting\n        if word in result:  # Dictionary membership check\n            result[word] += 1  # Increment count if word exists\n        else:\n            result[word] = 1\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef count_words():\n    user = input('type words: ').split()\n    sort = sorted(user)  # Sort words alphabetically\n    result = {}  # Dictionary to store word counts\n    for word in sort:\n        word = word.lower()  # Convert to lowercase for case-insensitive counting\n        if word in result:  # Dictionary membership check\n            result[word] += 1  # Increment count if word exists\n        else:\n            result[word] = 1\n    result = result\n    return result\n\n# Script approach\nstring = 'hello'\nresult = count_words(string)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(count_words('world'))",

