            "description": "Write a program that maps a list of words into a list of integers representing the lengths of the correponding words without using len().\nExamples:\n  length_words(['cat', 'horse']) → [3, 5]\n  length_words(['apple', 'pear']) → [5, 4]",
            "initialCode": "def length_words(lst):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef length_words(lst):\n    length = []\n    for word in lst:\n        count = 0\n        for char in word:\n            count += 1\n        length.append(count)\n    return length\nlst = ['Jonathan', 'chris', 'mountain']\nprint(length_words(lst))\n\n# Alternative using map with counter\ndef length_words(lst):\n    return [sum(1 for _ in w) for w in lst]\nprint(length_words(['Jonathan', 'chris', 'mountain']))\n\n# Alternative using enumerate\ndef length_words(lst):\n    result = []\n    for word in lst:\n        for i, _ in enumerate(word):\n        result.append(i + 1)\n    return result\nprint(length_words(['cat', 'horse']))  # Output: [3, 5]\n\n# Alternative using manual count with while\ndef length_words(lst):\n    return [len_manual(w) for w in lst]\ndef len_manual(s):\n    c = 0\n    for _ in s:\n        c += 1\n    return c\nprint(length_words(['apple', 'pear']))  # Output: [5, 4]\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef length_words(lst):\n    return [count for word in lst]\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef length_words(lst):\n    return list(map(lambda word: count, lst))\n\n# Script approach\nlst = [2, 4, 6, 8]\nresult = length_words(lst)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(length_words([1, 3, 5, 7]))",

