            "description": "Write a Python program to merge two dictionaries into one.\nExamples:\n  main({'a':1}, {'b':2}) → [object Object]\n  main({'a':1}, {'b':3}) → [object Object]",
            "initialCode": "def main(dic1, dic2):\n    pass\n\ndef merge_dicts(dic1, dic2):\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef main(dic1, dic2):\n    merge_dic = dic1.copy()  \n    for key, value in dic2.items():\n        if key in merge_dic:\n            merge_dic[key] = [merge_dic[key], value]\n        else:\n            merge_dic[key] = value\n    return merge_dic\ndic1 = {\n    'name': 777,\n    'age': 56,\n    'city': 34,\n    'job': 1\n}\ndic2 = {\n    'name': 2,\n    'age': 2,\n    'cities': 2,\n    'jobless': 2\n}\nprint(main(dic1, dic2))\ndef merge_dicts(dic1, dic2):\n    merged_dict = {**dic1, **dic2}\n    return merged_dict\ndic1 = {\n    'name': 'Steven',\n    'age': 56,\n    'city': 'New York',\n    'job': 'Engineer'\n}\ndic2 = {\n    'named': 'Alice',\n    'aged': 30,\n    'cities': 'New York',\n    'jobless': 'Engineer'\n}\nprint(merge_dicts(dic1, dic2))\n# Using alternative loop\n    # Consider using while loop or list comprehension\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef main(dic1, dic2):\n    result = merge_dic\n    return result\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef main(dic1, dic2):\n    return merge_dic\n\n# Script approach\ndic1 = 15\ndic2 = 15\nresult = main(dic1, dic2)\nprint(result)\n\n# Direct approach\nprint(main(25, 25))",

