            "description": "Use `default=` with `next()` to safely get the first item from a generator, or return a sentinel value.\nExamples:\n  number_gen() → <generator object number_gen at 0x107438280>",
            "initialCode": "def number_gen():\n    pass",
            "solution": "# Using function approach\ndef number_gen():\n    yield 1\n    yield 2\n    yield 3\ngen = number_gen()\nfirst = next(gen, 'END')\nempty_gen = iter([])\nempty_result = next(empty_gen, 'END')\nprint(first, empty_result)  # Expected: 1 END\n# Using different variable names\n    # Alternative: rewrite with different variable names and structure\n\n# Using built-in approach\ndef solve():\n    def number_gen():\n        yield 1\n        yield 2\n        yield 3\n    gen = number_gen()\n    first = next(gen, 'END')\n    empty_gen = iter([])\n    empty_result = next(empty_gen, 'END')\n    print(first, empty_result)  # Expected: 1 END\n\n# Using manual approach\ndef solve():\n    def number_gen():\n        yield 1\n        yield 2\n        yield 3\n    gen = number_gen()\n    first = next(gen, 'END')\n    empty_gen = iter([])\n    empty_result = next(empty_gen, 'END')\n    return first, empty_result\n\n# Script approach\nyield 1\nyield 2\nyield 3\n\n# Direct approach\nyield 1\nyield 2\nyield 3",

            "hint": "Generators use `yield` to produce values and `next()` or a `for` loop to consume them.\nA generator function returns a generator object (lazy iterator), not the values themselves.\nUse `return` to send the result back — `print()` alone will not satisfy a function problem.",
